speech.para:
The purpose of dividing a  . . . bill is to facilitate the Senate's consideration of a matter—to give the Senate an opportunity of voting separately and effectively on all the issues involved and, should it be necessary, to thwart any possible tacking provisions in a bill the effect of which may be to infringe the Senate's constitutional power of amendment. (

 Odgers, Australian Senate Practice,  6th ed., p 464


 )

